# Cursor AI Assistant Rules for Pacifica Trading Bot
# This file configures how Cursor's AI should interact with this codebase

[Project Context]
- This is a production trading bot for Pacifica perpetual DEX on Solana
- Two main components: data-collector (API polling) and signal-engine (signal processing)
- Python 3.11+, uses TA-Lib, Bytewax, QuestDB, and Parquet for storage
- Deployed on Fly.io with 24/7 data collection
- Critical: Never suggest changes that could lose historical data

[Code Style]
- Follow PEP 8 for Python
- Use type hints on all function signatures
- Prefer dataclasses over plain dicts for structured data
- Use pathlib.Path instead of string paths
- Import order: stdlib, third-party, local (separated by blank lines)
- Max line length: 100 characters
- Use f-strings for string formatting

[Architecture Rules]
- Keep data-collector and signal-engine separate - they're independent packages
- Data collector writes to Parquet partitioned by symbol= and date=
- Signal engine reads Parquet and writes to QuestDB
- Never mix business logic into storage/API layers
- All new signals must inherit from signals.base.Signal
- Backtest engine must remain deterministic (no randomness)

[Testing Requirements]
- Every new signal calculator MUST have unit tests
- Test file structure mirrors src/ structure
- Use pytest fixtures from tests/fixtures/sample_data.py
- Mock QuestDB in unit tests (use SKIP_QUESTDB_TESTS=true)
- Integration tests only run when QuestDB is available

[Security Rules]
- Never log API keys, even partially
- Never commit .env files (only .env.example)
- Use environment variables for ALL configuration
- Validate all external inputs (API responses, file data)
- Use parameterized queries for all database operations

[Data Handling]
- NEVER delete data/ or logs/ directories
- Parquet files are immutable once written
- Use atomic writes (write to .tmp then rename)
- Partition data by symbol and date for queryability
- Keep in-memory buffers under 5000 rows before flushing

[Dependencies]
- Check package compatibility before adding new dependencies
- TA-Lib requires system-level installation (brew/apt)
- Pin all versions in requirements.txt
- Test on both x86_64 and arm64 before committing

[Deployment]
- Changes to collect_all_symbols_cloud.py affect production immediately
- Test deployment configs locally with Docker first
- Fly.io free tier has 3GB storage limit - be mindful
- Health check endpoint MUST always respond within 5s

[Common Pitfalls to Avoid]
- Don't use localStorage/sessionStorage in HTML artifacts (not supported)
- Don't assume QuestDB COPY command works (has fallback to INSERT)
- Don't use blocking I/O in Bytewax dataflows
- Don't modify signal state during should_exit() checks
- Don't use mutable default arguments in Python
- Don't forget to update both Dockerfile AND Dockerfile.arm64

[File Modification Guidelines]
- When modifying signal logic, update corresponding tests
- When adding new signals, add to __all__ in signals/__init__.py
- When changing schemas, update both schema.sql AND models
- When modifying collectors, test with monitoring/check_collector.sh
- When changing deployment, update BOTH deployment docs

[Questions to Ask Before Making Changes]
1. Will this break existing backtests? (determinism required)
2. Will this affect data collection in production?
3. Does this require schema migration in QuestDB?
4. Have I tested on the target architecture (arm64 for M1/M2)?
5. Is this change documented in the appropriate README?

[Helpful Context Locations]
- Architecture overview: /signal-engine/src/backtest/README.md (if exists)
- API endpoints: src/collector/pacifica_rest.py
- Signal implementations: signal-engine/src/signals/
- Deployment guide: DEPLOYMENT_GUIDE.md
- Current deployment status: .collection-status.md

[When Uncertain]
- Check recent git history for similar changes
- Verify against production logs (if available)
- Test changes with --dry-run flags when available
- Ask for human review if touching deployment configs
